inhalt:
In this seminar, you will learn to analyze space exploration through the lens of its visual and material culture. Space exploration is not just a scientific endeavour—it is deeply embedded in human culture, politics, and imagination. From the iconic imagery of the Apollo Moon landings to the design of rockets by NewSpace entrepreneurs, and the commodification of space-themed merchandise, the visual and material cultures of space exploration reveal underlying ideologies, aspirations, and anxieties. By analyzing the past, present, and potential futures of space exploration through its visual representations and material artifacts, we gain critical insights into how humans envision, negotiate, and construct their place in the cosmos.

Through the thematic of space exploration, you will learn a variety of qualitative approaches and strategies to conducting visual and material culture analyses, including:
•	investigating the aesthetic and design elements of space-related imagery and objects;
•	situating artefacts within their cultural, political, and temporal contexts to uncover their broader meanings;
•	interpreting the signs, symbols, and metaphors that infuse space-related paraphernalia;
•	and exploring similarities and differences across cultures, time periods, or media.

Seminars will involve reading and discussing case studies together, practicing hands-on exercises to sharpen your analytic skills, and workshop-style sessions to help you hone your methodological approach. In the latter stages of the seminar, you will study a chosen image or object related to space exploration and present your findings.
